idegger, Derrida, Deleuze & Guattari and AgambenThe animality of human beings is completely unknown. Being human means to be something other than an animal, to not be an animal. Felice Cimatti, with reference to the work of Gilles Deleuze, explores what human animality looks like. He shows that becoming animal means to stop thinking of humanity as the reference point of nature and the world. It means that our value as humans has the very same value as a cloud, a rock or a spider.Drawing on a wide range of texts – from philosophical ethology to classical texts, and from continental philosophy to literature – Cimatti creates a dialogue with Flaubert, Derrida, Temple Grandin, Heidegger as well as Malaparte and Landolfi – as part of this intriguing discussion about our humanity – and our unknown animality. Literary Case StudiesFranz Kafka: 'The Wish to be a Red Indian' and 'A Report to an Academy'Temple Grandin: Animals in Translation: The Woman Who Thinks Like a Cow Curzio Malaparte: KaputtD. H. Lawrence: 'St Mawr' and 'The Man Who Died'Gustave Flaubert: 'La légende de saint-Julien l'Hospitalier'Romeo Castellucci's theatre  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAnimals (Philosophy). 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aGironi, Fabio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474443418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474443418/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13E